00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:27.730
PROFESSOR: --afternoon.

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:31.490
Our main subject for today
is the fine structure

00:00:31.490 --> 00:00:39.450
of atoms, when spin couples and
we bring spin into the picture.

00:00:39.450 --> 00:00:41.750
And if time permits,
a Lamb shift.

00:00:41.750 --> 00:00:43.650
But before I get
started, I just want

00:00:43.650 --> 00:00:49.512
to finish up our topic of the
last class, which was helium.

00:00:49.512 --> 00:00:53.020
And I said for many,
many years, we only

00:00:53.020 --> 00:00:57.240
discussed single electron atoms,
but I introduced the helium

00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:00.840
atom into the curriculum because
there are two aspects which

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:03.680
are really new and
which we can learn

00:01:03.680 --> 00:01:07.780
from helium with a
more simple example.

00:01:07.780 --> 00:01:17.080
One was the fact of
how the spin leads

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:21.540
to interactions even if nothing
couples directly to the spin.

00:01:21.540 --> 00:01:25.275
And we discussed it last
class that because we

00:01:25.275 --> 00:01:29.610
have singlet and triplet
states, they impose symmetry

00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:32.440
or anti-symmetry onto the
spatial wave function.

00:01:32.440 --> 00:01:34.910
And that makes a big
difference in the energy.

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:38.370
And it is sort of this
big Coulomb energy, which

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:40.810
is connected to spin,
which is actually

00:01:40.810 --> 00:01:44.590
responsible for
magnetism in nature.

00:01:44.590 --> 00:01:48.190
The second aspect, the
second new feature,

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:50.230
which is, of course,
also related to spin

00:01:50.230 --> 00:01:55.400
is the presence of singlet
and triplet states.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:57.390
And it gives me an
opportunity-- and this

00:01:57.390 --> 00:01:59.830
was the last point we
discussed on Wednesday--

00:01:59.830 --> 00:02:03.490
to raise the question,
what can cause

00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:08.400
a transition from
triplet to singlet?

00:02:08.400 --> 00:02:19.330
And at the end of
Wednesday's lecture,

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:23.600
we discussed the question,
what kind of couplings

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:27.185
would allow you want to drive
a transition from triplet

00:02:27.185 --> 00:02:28.860
to singlet?

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:33.060
And at least based on the
clicker result, for most of you

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:36.080
the surprising answer was none.

00:02:36.080 --> 00:02:37.320
Optical fields, not.

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:40.670
Rotating fields, not.

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:43.980
Within the approximation
we have so far-- namely,

00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:48.060
just a Hamiltonian with
Coulomb interaction--

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:50.620
there is nothing
in the system which

00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:55.100
connects the singlet
to the triplet world.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:57.050
Well, there is a
very weak transition,

00:02:57.050 --> 00:02:58.960
but the lifetime of
the triplet counts

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:01.750
it in helium, as I will
tell you a little bit later,

00:03:01.750 --> 00:03:03.220
is 8,000 seconds.

00:03:03.220 --> 00:03:04.760
It's extremely long life.

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:07.770
We have an extreme form
of metastability here.

00:03:07.770 --> 00:03:09.300
Just an anecdote.

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:11.920
In the early days
when people learned

00:03:11.920 --> 00:03:15.380
about the structure of atoms,
they looked at spectra.

00:03:15.380 --> 00:03:19.050
And they never
found any line which

00:03:19.050 --> 00:03:22.370
was connecting the singlet
states with the triplet states.

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:27.780
So it looked like if there were
two different forms of helium,

00:03:27.780 --> 00:03:29.750
orthohelium and parahelium.

00:03:29.750 --> 00:03:31.690
So people even
believed for a while

00:03:31.690 --> 00:03:33.880
there were two kinds
of helium in nature

00:03:33.880 --> 00:03:37.290
because they seemed to be
completely disconnected.

00:03:37.290 --> 00:03:39.910
But as we know now,
of course, this simply

00:03:39.910 --> 00:03:42.485
reflects the high
degree of metastability.

00:03:55.220 --> 00:03:58.750
I want to emphasize
before I give you

00:03:58.750 --> 00:04:02.020
the general framework and the
symmetry, spatial symmetry

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:03.890
and spin symmetry,
and we discuss all

00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:05.680
that in exchange
symmetry-- I want

00:04:05.680 --> 00:04:09.960
to emphasize what I said
at the end of the lecture

00:04:09.960 --> 00:04:10.900
on Wednesday.

00:04:10.900 --> 00:04:16.550
If you try to drive a transition
between singlet and triplet,

00:04:16.550 --> 00:04:20.440
if you use a rotating magnetic
field, you can't do that.

00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:25.380
Because a rotating magnetic
field couples to the total

00:04:25.380 --> 00:04:26.130
spin.

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:30.375
It just makes the
total spin precess

00:04:30.375 --> 00:04:34.080
around the axis of
the magnetic field.

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:37.460
But what the magnetic
field will never do

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:41.570
is break up the relative
angle between the two spins.

00:04:41.570 --> 00:04:44.900
And in a triplet state,
the two spins are aligned.

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:47.250
In the singlet states,
they are anti-aligned.

00:04:47.250 --> 00:04:49.590
And with a magnetic
field, you address

00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:51.520
both spins simultaneously.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:53.840
They precess together,
and you can never

00:04:53.840 --> 00:04:56.240
change the angle
between the two.

00:04:56.240 --> 00:04:58.120
So a singlet-triplet
transition really

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:00.630
requires that you go deeper.

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:06.590
You really have a handle on the
spins relative to each other.

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:09.530
Let me make a second comment
about the possibility

00:05:09.530 --> 00:05:11.253
of doing an optical transition.

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:19.610
An optical transition, at least
in the dipole approximation,

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:23.530
has an electric field
acting on the dipole moment

00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:25.710
of the electron.

00:05:25.710 --> 00:05:28.190
There is no spin involved.

00:05:28.190 --> 00:05:31.860
And let me sort of accentuate
it by saying, you should really

00:05:31.860 --> 00:05:35.520
have in your mind that, at
least in dipole approximation,

00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:41.350
the laser, the light, optical
beams, do not couple to spin.

00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:45.350
The only couple to the spatial
part of the wave function.

00:05:45.350 --> 00:05:50.830
And that has important
consequences.

00:05:50.830 --> 00:05:54.900
In a lot of our research,
we do Raman transitions.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:58.700
And with a Raman transition,
we do spin flips.

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.780
So how can a laser, or two
laser beams through a Raman

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:07.140
transition, flip the
spin if the laser is not

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:08.820
talking to the spin
degree of freedom?

00:06:12.370 --> 00:06:18.255
Well, if you have
a Raman transition

00:06:18.255 --> 00:06:22.730
and you excite a state which
has spin orbit coupling,

00:06:22.730 --> 00:06:24.360
you excite the atom.

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:26.850
The spin does nothing
during the excitation.

00:06:26.850 --> 00:06:31.270
But then in the
intermediate state,

00:06:31.270 --> 00:06:35.410
spin and angular momentum may be
coupled by spin orbit coupling.

00:06:35.410 --> 00:06:37.710
And the spin is
starting to precess

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:39.600
due to spin orbit coupling.

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:42.160
And then the spin
rotates, and then

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:44.620
the second leg of
the Raman transition

00:06:44.620 --> 00:06:46.810
transfers the atoms back
to the ground state,

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.450
but now the spin has rotated.

00:06:49.450 --> 00:06:52.410
But it is never the laser
which rotates the spin.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:56.880
What should be immediately
clear from that

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:58.910
is if you try to
have a spin flip

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:01.820
Raman transition in an atom
which has no spin orbit

00:07:01.820 --> 00:07:04.440
coupling don't
even look for that.

00:07:04.440 --> 00:07:07.230
It doesn't exist.

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:09.330
Anyway, we just
encountered it here

00:07:09.330 --> 00:07:12.660
and I want to tell
you that there is even

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:15.130
more general
consequences of that.

00:07:15.130 --> 00:07:18.750
But let's now go back
to the helium atom

00:07:18.750 --> 00:07:24.310
and look at the
spatial symmetry which

00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:27.250
comes, of course,
because operators

00:07:27.250 --> 00:07:29.715
are symmetric with regard
to the two electrons.

00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:39.860
So what we have is we
have the total spin

00:07:39.860 --> 00:07:45.650
is the sum of the spins of
electron 1 and electron 2.

00:07:48.350 --> 00:08:01.970
And all spin operators--
the spin operator s

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:09.566
and its components-- are
symmetric against particle

00:08:09.566 --> 00:08:10.065
exchange.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:17.150
In other words, if
you couple to the spin

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:20.860
through a magnetic field, you
couple to the two electrons

00:08:20.860 --> 00:08:22.670
symmetrically.

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:26.360
And therefore, you
have the selection

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:31.780
rule that only symmetric and
symmetric and anti-symmetric

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:33.559
and anti-symmetric
states couple.

00:08:36.200 --> 00:08:47.110
Or, to express the same result
in different words, both

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:56.540
the spatial and the spin
symmetry, each of them

00:08:56.540 --> 00:08:59.249
can be symmetric
and anti-symmetric.

00:08:59.249 --> 00:09:01.540
Of course, the product of
them has to be anti-symmetric

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:04.600
because we're talking
about fermions.

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:09.910
So both of these symmetries
are good quantum numbers.

00:09:18.530 --> 00:09:25.396
Or more formally, all
observables commute

00:09:25.396 --> 00:09:26.895
with the particle
exchange operator.

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:35.230
So any arbitrary
observable commute.

00:09:53.870 --> 00:09:58.540
So the commutator of the
particle exchange operator

00:09:58.540 --> 00:09:59.040
vanishes.

00:10:04.255 --> 00:10:04.755
OK.

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:10.530
But now, what is special
to the approximation

00:10:10.530 --> 00:10:12.970
in which we have treated helium?

00:10:12.970 --> 00:10:17.130
As long as wave
functions and operators

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:22.200
separate into spin-dependent
and space-dependent parts.

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:24.930
The wave function
had a spatial part,

00:10:24.930 --> 00:10:28.180
and then we multiplied
with a spin wave function.

00:10:28.180 --> 00:10:32.180
So the wave function
factor-wise separated

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:33.810
into a spin part
and a spatial part.

00:10:40.020 --> 00:10:40.921
Also, the operators.

00:10:40.921 --> 00:10:42.420
If you have operator
for total spin,

00:10:42.420 --> 00:10:45.200
if you have operator
for dipole moment,

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:47.120
the operators are
either addressing

00:10:47.120 --> 00:10:51.790
the spatial degree of freedom
or the spin degree of freedom.

00:10:51.790 --> 00:10:55.520
So as long as this
is the case, we

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:58.420
have an even extended
conservation law

00:10:58.420 --> 00:11:03.800
for both spin exchange for
an exchange of the particles

00:11:03.800 --> 00:11:07.030
in the spatial domain
and in the spin domain.

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:21.560
So as long as wave
functions and operators

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:36.910
separate into spin and
space-dependent parts,

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:41.080
then the particle
exchange operator

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:47.180
can be regarded as the product
of an exchange operator which

00:11:47.180 --> 00:11:49.926
only acts on the
spatial wave function

00:11:49.926 --> 00:11:51.675
and on the spin part
of the wave function.

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:04.450
And both quantum numbers
for spin exchange--

00:12:04.450 --> 00:12:07.730
symmetric/anti-symmetric--
and for exchange of particles

00:12:07.730 --> 00:12:09.960
in the spatial part
of the wave function,

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:13.220
symmetric or anti-symmetric--
are conserved.

00:12:27.530 --> 00:12:30.750
So often, we discuss
symmetries and the reason

00:12:30.750 --> 00:12:33.550
why something is
conserved because then we

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:36.770
can think about
how to evaluate it.

00:12:36.770 --> 00:12:39.480
Often, you can say,
conservation laws

00:12:39.480 --> 00:12:42.350
are often written down just
as a way to think about.

00:12:42.350 --> 00:12:44.900
How can we break them?

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:53.020
And in this case, we can
break this symmetries

00:12:53.020 --> 00:12:56.050
which doesn't allow transitions
between singlet and triplet.

00:12:56.050 --> 00:12:59.660
We have to break them to
get intercombination lines.

00:12:59.660 --> 00:13:08.490
So in order to get a singlet
to triplet transition,

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:10.401
it's only possible
when we violate

00:13:10.401 --> 00:13:12.025
the assumptions we
have just discussed.

00:13:28.330 --> 00:13:31.590
And of course, an assumption was
that the wave function factors

00:13:31.590 --> 00:13:34.580
into spin part and spatial part.

00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:36.930
But when spin and
spatial wave functions

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:38.320
are mixed-- for
instance, by spin

00:13:38.320 --> 00:13:41.630
orbit coupling-- then the
assumptions we have discussed

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:42.630
are no longer valid.

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:47.000
So what we need
is, for instance,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:55.770
a mixing of spin and
spatial wave functions

00:13:55.770 --> 00:13:56.905
by spin orbit coupling.

00:14:04.510 --> 00:14:07.800
Well, as we will
learn later today,

00:14:07.800 --> 00:14:13.270
spin orbit coupling
is, actually,

00:14:13.270 --> 00:14:14.600
a relativistic effect.

00:14:14.600 --> 00:14:17.010
It naturally arises
in the Dirac equation.

00:14:17.010 --> 00:14:23.690
And it scales with-- the
nuclear charge is z to the 4.

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:26.230
So therefore in helium,
it is very, very weak.

00:14:32.150 --> 00:14:46.000
Therefore, the triplet ground
state is extremely long-lived.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.860
The lifetime in helium
is 8,000 seconds.

00:14:49.860 --> 00:14:53.480
It's one of the most
longest-lived metastable states

00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:57.250
you can imagine and which
you find in atomic physics.

00:14:57.250 --> 00:15:03.730
Now, since spin orbit coupling
becomes rapidly stronger

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:09.010
with nuclear charge, you would
expect the metastable lifetime

00:15:09.010 --> 00:15:12.390
to be much shorter
for the analogous

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:15.100
state in the other rare gases.

00:15:15.100 --> 00:15:17.500
And indeed, the
other rare gasses

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:19.300
are on the order of 40 seconds.

00:15:27.270 --> 00:15:30.510
You have other atoms where you
have singlet and triplet lines.

00:15:34.832 --> 00:15:38.100
We need two electrons
and the two spins

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:39.920
can form singlet or triplet.

00:15:39.920 --> 00:15:44.670
So that naturally
also happens in atoms

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:48.470
which are in the second
column of the periodic table.

00:15:48.470 --> 00:15:54.360
Magnesium, calcium, strontium
have intercombination lines.

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:05.910
And they are actually very
relevant in current research

00:16:05.910 --> 00:16:11.625
because these are candidates
for atomic clocks.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:20.040
In those atoms--
magnesium, calcium,

00:16:20.040 --> 00:16:24.130
strontium-- physics
is more complicated.

00:16:24.130 --> 00:16:26.660
The line width is
typically kilohertz.

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:33.250
But that's probably
just what you want.

00:16:33.250 --> 00:16:37.270
If the line width is kilohertz,
the lifetime is millisecond.

00:16:37.270 --> 00:16:39.850
You still have a
matrix element that you

00:16:39.850 --> 00:16:42.180
can drive the transition
and observe it.

00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:44.580
For an atomic clock, you
don't want a transition

00:16:44.580 --> 00:16:50.270
which is thousands of seconds
or half the age of the universe

00:16:50.270 --> 00:16:54.330
because it's too weak to be
observed, to weak to be driven.

00:16:54.330 --> 00:16:57.402
So intercombination
lines of kilohertz,

00:16:57.402 --> 00:16:59.110
line widths of few
hundred Hertz or such,

00:16:59.110 --> 00:17:03.200
are almost ideal for
optical atomic clocks.

00:17:07.230 --> 00:17:08.619
Any questions?

00:17:14.670 --> 00:17:19.619
So maybe then I should just
entertain you for a few minutes

00:17:19.619 --> 00:17:26.086
about, how do you measure
an 8,000 second lifetime?

00:17:26.086 --> 00:17:33.818
Well, there is a recent paper.

00:17:33.818 --> 00:17:34.460
Insert Picture.

00:17:34.460 --> 00:17:34.960
Desktop.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:48.730
There's a recent
paper a few years ago,

00:17:48.730 --> 00:17:50.900
Physical Review
Letters, determination

00:17:50.900 --> 00:17:54.570
of the lifetime of
metastable helium.

00:17:54.570 --> 00:17:56.970
Traditionally, people
have measured the lifetime

00:17:56.970 --> 00:17:59.330
of metastable helium
in the following way.

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:02.550
No, they haven't observed
helium for 8,000 seconds.

00:18:02.550 --> 00:18:05.400
Because if you have helium
in the metastable state,

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:08.200
maybe after a few seconds there
is some collisions-- collision

00:18:08.200 --> 00:18:09.410
or deactivation.

00:18:09.410 --> 00:18:11.080
8,000 seconds, you
would just have

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:12.940
many, many systematic effects.

00:18:12.940 --> 00:18:19.960
What people did is
they put some atoms

00:18:19.960 --> 00:18:23.420
into the metastable state,
measured the number of excited

00:18:23.420 --> 00:18:28.550
atoms, and then-- maybe
during 100 milliseconds,

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:32.000
1 out of 80,000
atoms should decay.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.070
And by determining what
small fraction of the atoms

00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:37.695
has decayed, or how
many photons you observe

00:18:37.695 --> 00:18:41.350
in 100 milliseconds divided
by the total number of atoms,

00:18:41.350 --> 00:18:43.690
that's how you can
measure the lifetime.

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:45.600
Of course, the
problem is, yes, you

00:18:45.600 --> 00:18:47.020
can measure the
number of photons.

00:18:47.020 --> 00:18:49.061
But if you want to divide
by the number of atoms,

00:18:49.061 --> 00:18:52.310
you have to know very accurately
how many atoms you have.

00:18:52.310 --> 00:18:59.430
And this Australian group
used the very clever trick

00:18:59.430 --> 00:19:02.570
to eliminate this uncertainty.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:16.680
And this is as follows.

00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:21.400
We have this extremely
long-lived 8,000 seconds

00:19:21.400 --> 00:19:22.580
lifetime here.

00:19:22.580 --> 00:19:24.450
And this is the transition.

00:19:24.450 --> 00:19:33.920
But you can now excite the atom
to the triplet P0 state, which

00:19:33.920 --> 00:19:36.195
is also sort of--
it's a triplet state.

00:19:39.720 --> 00:19:43.980
Well, I assume because
it is a P state,

00:19:43.980 --> 00:19:45.430
it has been orbit coupling.

00:19:45.430 --> 00:19:48.150
The lifetime is-- well,
for an atom is very long.

00:19:48.150 --> 00:19:50.000
Typically, atoms
decay in nanoseconds.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.180
But this lifetime
is milliseconds.

00:19:52.180 --> 00:19:55.690
So what they did is they
just excited all the atoms

00:19:55.690 --> 00:19:59.870
with a strongly saturating laser
to the triplet P0 transition.

00:19:59.870 --> 00:20:01.890
And then within a
few milliseconds,

00:20:01.890 --> 00:20:03.850
all the atoms emitted.

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:06.380
And so all they had to
do is measure accurately

00:20:06.380 --> 00:20:12.360
the ratio of the VUV photons
emitted by the triplet ground

00:20:12.360 --> 00:20:16.330
state and by the
triplet P0 state.

00:20:16.330 --> 00:20:19.950
And then the number
of atoms canceled out.

00:20:19.950 --> 00:20:26.830
All they had to do is measure
the ratio of 2 VUV intensities.

00:20:26.830 --> 00:20:30.180
So based on that research
now, we have higher accuracy

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:36.930
